title: Yet another 820-3115. Has a green light, but no power.
message:
It is trying to power on that is why you have unstable voltages. Check PP5V_S3 with a scope to see if there are any pulses there, multimeter is too slow.
Must be liquid or drop, inspect closely.

title: Yet another 820-3115. Has a green light, but no power.
message:
I dont have a scope yet.
Is there an alternative move I can make?

title: Yet another 820-3115. Has a green light, but no power.
message: Nope, I have no idea how slow your multimeter is and if it is able to see the short pulses.

title: Yet another 820-3115. Has a green light, but no power.
message:
OK, while I try and track down a scope, maybe we can start checking from another angle.

[COLOR=#333333][FONT=Verdana]PM_SLP_S4_L is reading at 0, where does it come from?
U1800 it seems, so why is it not sending anything?[/FONT][/COLOR]

title: Yet another 820-3115. Has a green light, but no power.
message: It may also be pulsing......this is what these boards do if something is wrong in the power sequence.

title: Yet another 820-3115. Has a green light, but no power.
message:
[USER="2"]dukefawks[/USER] could the unstable PP3v3_SUS be because it is trying to start up and something is tripping or failing?

If there was no PM_SLP_S4_L it would just remain in an off state, but it appears that it is trying to progress along.

My thoughts being that it isn't U1800 not creating the S4_L it is simply cycling before it get's that far.

title: Yet another 820-3115. Has a green light, but no power.
message: I really don't know. Check voltage to R1800/1/2/3, R1915, C2231/32/33.
